I just don't see why anyone- theist, atheist, or Martian, should ever have an agenda to push on anyone except themselves. Atheist proselytizing is just as bad as any other form (though I have to admit, I very rarely, if ever, have seen it) of infringement. I don't see positively asserting atheism over other forms of belief (and I know, atheism is not a belief) as any more productive than the JW who comes and knocks on my door.<br>
<br>
Belief or non belief is an intensely personal thing, and although I will fight for my right for my society at large to be a religion neutral arena- my schools, the workplace, the government, things of that order, I don't take it into the personal realm, like this debate board ( I can debate, but I don't take it into &quot;faith is bad&quot;), because I don't see the point. It's imposing on others' experiences and life expectations. <br>
<br>
I don't see it as idly sitting by. I completely resent the implication that by me not choosing to tell religious people that they are misguided or wrong that I am helping the &quot;other&quot; side. When I see religion misplaced in society, I have a case to stand on the merits of privacy and freedom rights on its own. There is no need for me to positively assert atheism in those instances. In most cases, those are unlawful uses, and that's why I belong to the ACLU, and NARAL. I see it as trying, through what I believe (or don't believe), to live the best life I can, and hopefully, by example, others will get the point. I think it's the best we can hope for. I fight to keep religion out of the places it doesn't belong, but I would never make the universal proclamation that faith is bad, because it's not a blanket statement.<br>
<br>
I have no need of faith, and see no use in it, but for others, there is a need it fulfills, and it satisfies a part of them in a way that other things can't.  I think, for me,  acknowledging that is a very necessary step towards understanding human nature. I can't convert those around me to atheism. I can only be honest about what I feel, what I've learned, and what I've gleaned about how it all works. But for it to be a genuine experience, it has to come from them. Deconversion is just as important as conversion, in terms of the motivation.<br>
