ions like the ‘Faith = Bad’ one for the purpose of issuing challenges and shaking up a calcified notion.  It makes people think.  It tugs at their gut and forces them to prove just why it isn’t, or equally possibly, it gives them pause to discard it.  When everyone is arguing the color of the unicorn, someone needs to ask if there really is a unicorn.  I don’t disagree that for them to genuinely convert, it has to come from them, but our audience is larger than dag and Candy.  I don’t expect them to convert ever (though Candy would be a wonderful atheist.)  We have more than 10 times as many viewers to these discussions as we do posters.  People are reading, that means they are thinking.  If no one shows them how we think and why, they may not ever come to it themselves.  If just one person walks away and checks out ‘Demon Haunted World’ or ‘Why We Believe’ when they otherwise may never have heard of them, I think we have helped them.  You are correct, we cannot make them drink, but we can show them where we get our water and explain why it tastes so much sweeter than their wine.<br>
